1
00:00:55,388 --> 00:00:57,481
<i>My name is Anne Blair.</i>

2
00:00:57,657 --> 00:01:00,751
<i>My father was Dr. Julian Blair.</i>

3
00:01:00,927 --> 00:01:03,487
<i>This was my father's house.</i>

4
00:01:04,030 --> 00:01:07,090
<i>In Barsham Harbor,</i>
<i>on nights like this...</i>

5
00:01:07,267 --> 00:01:09,861
<i>...when lightning rips the night apart...</i>

6
00:01:10,036 --> 00:01:14,302
<i>...why do people close the shutters</i>
<i>that face towards my father's house?</i>

7
00:01:14,474 --> 00:01:17,671
<i>And lock their doors and whisper?</i>

8
00:01:17,844 --> 00:01:20,404
<i>Why are they afraid?</i>

9
00:01:20,580 --> 00:01:23,413
<i>No one goes near my father's house.</i>

10
00:01:23,583 --> 00:01:26,211
<i>No one dares.</i>

11
00:01:26,853 --> 00:01:29,321
<i>I don't know where my father is.</i>

12
00:01:29,489 --> 00:01:32,754
<i>I only know that for one</i>
<i>brief terrible moment...</i>

13
00:01:32,926 --> 00:01:36,229
<i>...he tore open the door</i>
<i>to whatever lives beyond the grave.</i>

14
00:01:36,229 --> 00:01:36,820
<i>...he tore open the door</i>
<i>to whatever lives beyond the grave.</i>

15
00:01:37,897 --> 00:01:41,264
<i>Seven years ago, my father was</i>
<i>head of the science department...</i>

16
00:01:41,434 --> 00:01:43,129
<i>...at Midland University...</i>

17
00:01:43,470 --> 00:01:46,200
<i>...a few hundred miles</i>
<i>from Barsham Harbor.</i>

18
00:01:46,372 --> 00:01:48,670
<i>My father was famous.</i>

19
00:01:48,842 --> 00:01:51,606
<i>They were proud of him</i>
<i>at the university.</i>

20
00:01:52,879 --> 00:01:57,145
<i>That night, five great scientists</i>
<i>came to my father's laboratory...</i>

21
00:01:57,784 --> 00:02:01,686
<i>...to see something no one</i>
<i>on earth had ever seen before.</i>

22
00:02:02,489 --> 00:02:05,219
Finally ready to startle us, Dr. Blair?

23
00:02:05,692 --> 00:02:08,422
l don't blame you for being skeptical,
Professor Kent...

24
00:02:08,595 --> 00:02:11,189
...but l assure you that
all this is vitally necessary...

25
00:02:11,364 --> 00:02:14,356
...for the demonstration
l've invited you here to witness.

26
00:02:15,135 --> 00:02:16,602
You will be the first people...

27
00:02:16,769 --> 00:02:20,227
...with the exception of my wife
and my assistant, Dr. Sayles...

28
00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:22,499
...to see the proof
that the human brain...

29
00:02:22,675 --> 00:02:25,439
...gives off an impulse
that can be recorded.

30
00:02:27,247 --> 00:02:30,182
l think we'd better close
those blinds, Saunders.

31
00:02:44,063 --> 00:02:46,054
Please watch the chart, gentlemen.

32
00:03:10,323 --> 00:03:14,953
Dr. Sayles' brain is sending out the
waves you see recorded on that chart.

33
00:03:15,495 --> 00:03:17,463
And whether he speaks or is silent...

34
00:03:17,630 --> 00:03:21,225
...or even if he tried to hide what he was
thinking with meaningless words...

35
00:03:21,401 --> 00:03:24,928
...his true thoughts would
still be recorded on that chart.

36
00:03:25,205 --> 00:03:28,003
-How did you reach that conclusion?
-Well...

37
00:03:28,408 --> 00:03:33,436
...you will notice a repeated pattern
in the variant waves, an exact rhythm...

38
00:03:33,613 --> 00:03:35,638
...as though it were a carrier wave...

39
00:03:35,815 --> 00:03:38,079
...on which the true thoughts
were being transmitted.

40
00:03:40,119 --> 00:03:41,916
l think we better stop now.

41
00:03:48,561 --> 00:03:51,530
-You feel any ill effects?
-Not at all, Dr. Saunders.

42
00:03:51,764 --> 00:03:54,028
So that's a portrait
of the mind of Dr. Sayles.

43
00:03:54,200 --> 00:03:56,430
-Yes, Dr. Hart.
-A poor thing, but mine own.

44
00:03:56,603 --> 00:03:59,003
-Seems incredible.
-Can you make a graph like that...

45
00:03:59,172 --> 00:04:01,072
-...for any living brain?
-Oh, yes.

46
00:04:01,241 --> 00:04:03,266
And each brain has
its own wavelength...

47
00:04:03,443 --> 00:04:05,968
...and they're as unlike as fingerprints.

48
00:04:10,149 --> 00:04:11,275
Excuse me.

49
00:04:12,285 --> 00:04:14,583
l couldn't help it.
She said it was important.

50
00:04:14,754 --> 00:04:16,813
-Helen!
-Don't blame Karl.

51
00:04:16,990 --> 00:04:18,958
-You're not angry, are you?
-Of course not.

52
00:04:19,125 --> 00:04:20,888
Come on in.
You know everybody here.

53
00:04:21,327 --> 00:04:22,988
-Hello, Richard.
-Hello, Mrs. Blair.

54
00:04:23,162 --> 00:04:24,789
-Good evening.
-How are you?

55
00:04:24,964 --> 00:04:28,695
l hope you'll forgive me for interrupting,
but l know my husband so well.

56
00:04:28,868 --> 00:04:30,426
When he gets started in the lab...

57
00:04:30,603 --> 00:04:33,800
...he forgets about time
and people and everything.

58
00:04:33,973 --> 00:04:36,703
You have forgotten, dear,
haven't you?

59
00:04:37,143 --> 00:04:39,373
Anne is coming home this evening.

60
00:04:39,812 --> 00:04:42,838
Anne is our daughter, and she's
been visiting friends in New York.

61
00:04:43,016 --> 00:04:45,780
Today's her 20th birthday.
l remembered that.

62
00:04:45,952 --> 00:04:48,887
-lf we don't hurry, we'll be late.
-Helen, wait a minute.

63
00:04:49,055 --> 00:04:50,113
We've still got time.

64
00:04:50,290 --> 00:04:52,588
l was showing them
the recording with Richard.

65
00:04:52,759 --> 00:04:55,523
Now l'd like to show them
your graph for comparison.

66
00:04:55,695 --> 00:04:58,892
-But it's so late, darling.
-Oh, please, dear, it won't take a minute.

67
00:04:59,065 --> 00:05:00,589
l'm not really Julian's wife.

68
00:05:00,767 --> 00:05:03,327
l'm guinea pig number one
for his experiments.

69
00:05:03,503 --> 00:05:06,233
And l guess l still like it
after all these years.

70
00:05:06,406 --> 00:05:07,737
l envy you, doctor.

71
00:05:07,907 --> 00:05:10,341
-A wonderful wife for a scientist.
-For any man.

72
00:05:10,510 --> 00:05:11,602
Thanks.

73
00:05:14,681 --> 00:05:16,740
-Are you sure your hair isn't wet?
-No, no.

74
00:05:16,916 --> 00:05:19,146
-Sure?
-Sure.

75
00:05:25,692 --> 00:05:29,321
You reset the graph, please, Richard.

76
00:06:00,193 --> 00:06:02,218
See how different the wavelengths are?

77
00:06:02,395 --> 00:06:04,488
Why should this record
be so much stronger?

78
00:06:04,664 --> 00:06:08,794
l don't know, but every demonstration
that l've made so far...

79
00:06:08,968 --> 00:06:12,904
...clearly shows the wave impulse
of woman, the so-called weaker sex...

80
00:06:13,072 --> 00:06:16,633
...is much stronger and is
much more regular than man's.

81
00:06:20,380 --> 00:06:23,713
Evidently, there's a greater natural power
in the brain of woman.

82
00:06:23,883 --> 00:06:26,875
-Any woman.
-Haven't l always told you that, Julian?

83
00:06:27,053 --> 00:06:31,387
-Has Mrs. Blair's graph ever varied?
-The individual wavelength never varies.

84
00:06:31,557 --> 00:06:33,718
Well, l believe what l can see.

85
00:06:33,893 --> 00:06:35,758
Now tell me where you go from there.

86
00:06:35,928 --> 00:06:41,093
Well, eventually, conceivably,
we may be able to record and read...

87
00:06:41,267 --> 00:06:44,703
...the thoughts of every human brain
without a word being spoken.

88
00:06:44,871 --> 00:06:48,102
You actually believe that someday
you can push a button here...

89
00:06:48,274 --> 00:06:50,435
...and read what
l'm thinking in Chicago?

90
00:06:50,610 --> 00:06:53,841
-You'll be able to read my thoughts too.
-lmpossible.

91
00:06:54,013 --> 00:06:56,846
They called radio impossible,
but all this that you see...

92
00:06:57,016 --> 00:06:59,450
...is only the first step towards
what we can achieve.

93
00:06:59,619 --> 00:07:02,554
lt may take years, perhaps a lifetime.

94
00:07:03,156 --> 00:07:05,920
But if science can unlock
the human mind...

95
00:07:06,092 --> 00:07:09,425
...can uncover the secrets
of every human brain...

96
00:07:09,595 --> 00:07:11,927
...well, that's a job worth doing,
Professor Kent.

97
00:07:12,098 --> 00:07:14,692
That's the first understatement
l've heard you make.

98
00:07:14,934 --> 00:07:17,266
l'd like to show them
the laboratory notes, Richard.

99
00:07:17,437 --> 00:07:19,268
-l'll get them.
-Richard, get his coat.

100
00:07:19,439 --> 00:07:20,838
-We've got to go.
-That's right.

101
00:07:21,007 --> 00:07:23,134
l'll have to leave you
with Dr. Sayles.

102
00:07:23,309 --> 00:07:25,300
-You see, l'm helpless.
-Sorry, gentlemen.

103
00:07:25,478 --> 00:07:26,467
Good night.

104
00:07:26,946 --> 00:07:30,313
-Do hurry, Julian.
-l'm sure we've got plenty of time, dear.

105
00:07:30,483 --> 00:07:33,043
Richard, l forgot to turn off
those switches.

106
00:07:33,219 --> 00:07:34,481
l'll take care of that.

107
00:07:34,654 --> 00:07:36,747
-We'll see you at the house later.
-All right.

108
00:07:36,923 --> 00:07:38,788
Come along, Julian.
Hurry up.

109
00:07:51,838 --> 00:07:52,862
You know...

110
00:07:53,039 --> 00:07:57,135
...l think l even convinced Professor
Kent, and that's a major triumph.

111
00:07:57,310 --> 00:08:00,143
Darling, don't be a scientist
anymore tonight.

112
00:08:00,313 --> 00:08:03,407
You're asking an awful lot, but l'll try.

113
00:08:12,892 --> 00:08:15,690
Say, aren't we going the wrong way
for the station?

114
00:08:15,862 --> 00:08:19,161
You've forgotten again, haven't you?

115
00:08:19,332 --> 00:08:22,495
l told you l was ordering
a birthday cake for Anne's party...

116
00:08:22,668 --> 00:08:25,535
-...with her name on it, remember?
-Oh, yes.

117
00:08:26,439 --> 00:08:30,398
-l don't see how you put up with me.
-lt's because you're you.

118
00:08:31,177 --> 00:08:33,577
l don't see anywhere to park, do you?

119
00:08:34,580 --> 00:08:37,777
Run out and get the cake,
and l'll drive around and pick you up.

120
00:08:37,950 --> 00:08:40,714
And hurry, dear. lt's almost train time.

121
00:08:48,361 --> 00:08:50,693
-Come for the birthday cake?
-Yes, Mr. Booth.

122
00:08:50,863 --> 00:08:53,627
Well, it's all ready for you.

123
00:08:57,570 --> 00:08:59,504
-Okay, doc?
-You're an artist.

124
00:08:59,672 --> 00:09:02,971
Well, l try to be,
especially for nice folks.

125
00:09:03,142 --> 00:09:06,168
Bet you and Mrs. Blair are happy
to have the young lady back.

126
00:09:06,345 --> 00:09:08,472
-lndeed we are.
-l'll carry it out for you.

127
00:09:08,648 --> 00:09:13,017
-l wanna say hello to Mrs. Blair anyhow.
-Thank you very much.

128
00:09:30,703 --> 00:09:31,965
Helen.

129
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:38,009
Helen.

130
00:09:41,113 --> 00:09:43,809
<i>I lost my mother that night.</i>

131
00:09:44,784 --> 00:09:47,912
<i>And when she went away...</i>

132
00:09:48,254 --> 00:09:51,485
<i>...I seemed to lose my father too.</i>

133
00:09:51,991 --> 00:09:54,459
<i>He loved her so much.</i>

134
00:09:56,395 --> 00:09:59,421
<i>I did all I could</i>
<i>to take my mother's place.</i>

135
00:09:59,799 --> 00:10:02,393
<i>He didn't seem to know I was there.</i>

136
00:10:03,069 --> 00:10:04,661
<i>He was lost.</i>

137
00:10:04,904 --> 00:10:06,599
<i>Alone.</i>

138
00:10:07,273 --> 00:10:09,639
<i>There wasn't anything</i>
<i>I could say to him.</i>

139
00:10:09,809 --> 00:10:12,300
<i>There wasn't anything I could do.</i>

140
00:10:12,778 --> 00:10:14,643
l'll get the car.

141
00:10:14,814 --> 00:10:16,372
No, Richard.

142
00:10:16,549 --> 00:10:18,483
You take Anne home.

143
00:10:18,651 --> 00:10:21,814
l want to walk for a while and think.

144
00:10:27,994 --> 00:10:28,628
<i>He went back to his laboratory</i>
<i>that night.</i>

145
00:10:28,628 --> 00:10:30,892
<i>He went back to his laboratory</i>
<i>that night.</i>

146
00:10:31,063 --> 00:10:32,360
<i>Alone.</i>

147
00:10:33,165 --> 00:10:35,725
<i>He couldn't bear being in our house...</i>

148
00:10:36,002 --> 00:10:39,494
<i>...where everything reminded him</i>
<i>of my mother.</i>

149
00:11:25,785 --> 00:11:26,774
Helen.

150
00:11:31,857 --> 00:11:33,085
Helen.

151
00:11:41,667 --> 00:11:42,793
Anne...

152
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:45,265
...for a moment, l thought that....

153
00:11:45,438 --> 00:11:47,565
Father, what's the matter?

154
00:11:48,774 --> 00:11:50,469
Anne, dear...

155
00:11:50,643 --> 00:11:54,170
...your mother is not dead, not really.

156
00:11:54,747 --> 00:11:56,510
She's come back to me.

157
00:11:57,516 --> 00:11:59,108
No, dear...

158
00:11:59,285 --> 00:12:01,219
...l haven't lost my mind.

159
00:12:01,687 --> 00:12:04,349
She's here, here in this room.

160
00:12:04,957 --> 00:12:06,822
She still lives.

161
00:12:07,993 --> 00:12:09,460
Look.

162
00:12:14,567 --> 00:12:15,868
l can only tell you again...

163
00:12:15,868 --> 00:12:16,800
l can only tell you again...

164
00:12:17,169 --> 00:12:19,103
...that when l turned on those motors...

165
00:12:19,271 --> 00:12:21,967
...it was simply because
l had to be doing something.

166
00:12:22,141 --> 00:12:24,200
l wasn't trying to reach my wife.

167
00:12:24,376 --> 00:12:27,743
l had no reason on earth
to believe that l could reach her.

168
00:12:28,481 --> 00:12:31,109
But she tried to reach me.

169
00:12:31,283 --> 00:12:35,379
There is the proof of something
the world has always wanted to believe.

170
00:12:35,654 --> 00:12:38,145
The proof of life after death.

171
00:12:40,993 --> 00:12:45,157
Richard. You of all people,
you've worked with me.

172
00:12:45,564 --> 00:12:49,125
You know how we believe
that mind could talk to mind.

173
00:12:49,535 --> 00:12:53,369
Well, now l know that there is a way
for the dead to talk to the living.

174
00:12:54,240 --> 00:12:58,108
My wife has passed through
a change that we call death.

175
00:12:58,377 --> 00:13:00,971
But the impulse that spoke
from her living brain...

176
00:13:01,147 --> 00:13:04,981
...that you saw me record
on that chart, did not die.

177
00:13:05,151 --> 00:13:08,848
lf Helen could send me that message,
and she did send it...

178
00:13:09,221 --> 00:13:13,055
...then there must be a way
to establish controlled and scientific...

179
00:13:13,225 --> 00:13:17,685
...communication between
the living and the so-called dead.

180
00:13:18,030 --> 00:13:20,999
Do you really believe what you say?

181
00:13:22,802 --> 00:13:27,603
Do you think l would invent
a story like that about my wife?

182
00:13:28,941 --> 00:13:33,310
How do you propose to go about
establishing this communication?

183
00:13:34,013 --> 00:13:38,074
Radio began with a first,
faint, transmitted impulse...

184
00:13:38,250 --> 00:13:40,616
...which no one knew
how to control or harness.

185
00:13:40,886 --> 00:13:44,117
Yet science found a way
to send sound and speech...

186
00:13:44,290 --> 00:13:47,088
...and living images
clear around the world.

187
00:13:47,860 --> 00:13:51,921
Well, l believe that the human brain,
the brain that invented radio...

188
00:13:52,498 --> 00:13:56,901
...is itself the most perfect sending
and receiving mechanism on earth.

189
00:13:57,069 --> 00:13:59,970
And l know that power
does not end with the grave.

190
00:14:00,506 --> 00:14:01,700
Don't you see?

191
00:14:01,874 --> 00:14:04,468
We hold in our hand a key
that may unlock the door...

192
00:14:04,643 --> 00:14:07,009
...between us and those
whom we call dead.

193
00:14:07,179 --> 00:14:09,704
lf we can set humanity free from fear...

194
00:14:09,882 --> 00:14:13,716
...if we can show people that those
we love are not lost to us...

195
00:14:13,886 --> 00:14:15,581
...if we can wipe out the horror...

196
00:14:15,754 --> 00:14:18,587
...that superstition conjures
up out of fear of darkness--

197
00:14:18,757 --> 00:14:19,781
Julian.

198
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:24,957
l have too much respect
for you to scoff at your hopes...

199
00:14:25,130 --> 00:14:27,826
...to doubt your utter sincerity.

200
00:14:28,334 --> 00:14:33,704
But what if you do find a way to pierce
the veil between us and them?

201
00:14:33,939 --> 00:14:36,874
And let the world of the dead
back in upon the living?

202
00:14:37,042 --> 00:14:40,409
We don't know what evil
may be lurking behind that veil...

203
00:14:40,579 --> 00:14:41,807
...waiting to get through.

204
00:14:41,981 --> 00:14:43,676
What if you let loose on humanity...

205
00:14:43,849 --> 00:14:47,376
...something much more terrible
than any fear that haunts us now?

206
00:14:48,020 --> 00:14:51,547
-But why should that happen?
-l know one thing, Julian.

207
00:14:51,924 --> 00:14:55,189
There are things human being
have no right to know.

208
00:14:55,461 --> 00:14:57,520
There speaks fear, even from you.

209
00:14:57,696 --> 00:15:02,099
Call it fear if you want to. l tell you,
you must not go on with this.

210
00:15:02,268 --> 00:15:06,329
Must not? ls there a wall beyond
which science may not go?

211
00:15:06,505 --> 00:15:09,872
-This is not science.
-Please don't argue.

212
00:15:10,042 --> 00:15:11,168
Anne.

213
00:15:12,945 --> 00:15:15,505
Don't argue with him,
because he's not himself.

214
00:15:15,814 --> 00:15:17,975
That's what's in your mind, isn't it?

215
00:15:18,851 --> 00:15:22,014
You won't believe me.
You won't help me.

216
00:15:22,688 --> 00:15:25,213
Poor, frightened little people.

217
00:15:25,691 --> 00:15:27,181
Well, l don't need you.

218
00:15:27,493 --> 00:15:28,960
l don't need any of you.

219
00:15:29,128 --> 00:15:32,188
Dad, won't you come
home now and rest?

220
00:15:32,364 --> 00:15:35,697
Then tomorrow,
maybe you'll feel better.

221
00:15:35,901 --> 00:15:37,095
Tomorrow.

222
00:15:37,636 --> 00:15:38,762
No, Anne.

223
00:15:38,938 --> 00:15:43,773
l'm not some helpless child
to be taken home for his own good.

224
00:15:45,177 --> 00:15:48,237
Get out. Get out.
All of you.

225
00:15:48,948 --> 00:15:50,279
Do you hear me, Anne?

226
00:15:50,449 --> 00:15:52,076
Go home.

227
00:15:52,451 --> 00:15:54,043
Thank you, gentlemen.

228
00:15:54,386 --> 00:15:57,014
Thank you for your great faith in me.

229
00:16:28,220 --> 00:16:29,278
What do you want?

230
00:16:29,455 --> 00:16:32,481
l just wanna tell you
you're right, doc. l know.

231
00:16:33,292 --> 00:16:36,659
-What are you talking about?
-l know we can talk to the dead.

232
00:16:36,829 --> 00:16:38,990
l talk to my mama all the time.

233
00:16:39,164 --> 00:16:42,600
She died two years ago,
but l can still talk to her.

234
00:16:42,768 --> 00:16:45,566
-How?
-Ever hear of Mrs. Blanche Walters?

235
00:16:45,738 --> 00:16:47,103
She's a spirit medium.

236
00:16:47,272 --> 00:16:49,934
Her control brings the voice to you
from the beyond.

237
00:16:50,109 --> 00:16:53,601
l'm afraid mediums
are no good to me, Karl.

238
00:16:55,080 --> 00:16:57,344
You better go now,
l've got work to do.

239
00:16:57,516 --> 00:16:58,915
But, doc...

240
00:16:59,084 --> 00:17:03,020
...it wouldn't hurt to see what
Mrs. Walters can do, would it?

241
00:17:06,225 --> 00:17:07,317
No.

242
00:17:09,261 --> 00:17:10,660
No.

243
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:13,098
<i>That night, my father took another step</i>
<i>toward tragedy.</i>

244
00:17:13,098 --> 00:17:17,694
<i>That night, my father took another step</i>
<i>toward tragedy.</i>

245
00:17:18,871 --> 00:17:23,331
<i>Poor Karl wasn't to blame.</i>
<i>Perhaps no one was to blame.</i>

246
00:17:23,842 --> 00:17:25,605
<i>I don't know.</i>

247
00:17:26,445 --> 00:17:29,710
<i>But that night, my father</i>
<i>met Mrs. Walters...</i>

248
00:17:29,882 --> 00:17:32,009
<i>...and then for him...</i>

249
00:17:32,184 --> 00:17:34,982
<i>...there was no turning back.</i>

250
00:17:35,821 --> 00:17:39,917
There is one here
who seeks his mother...

251
00:17:41,160 --> 00:17:44,687
...who asks his mother
to speak to him.

252
00:17:45,931 --> 00:17:49,128
His name is C....

253
00:17:50,502 --> 00:17:51,730
K....

254
00:17:52,271 --> 00:17:53,704
Karl.

255
00:17:54,640 --> 00:17:57,131
Karl seeks his mother.

256
00:17:58,710 --> 00:18:00,007
ls Karl here?

257
00:18:00,746 --> 00:18:01,735
Here.

258
00:18:02,114 --> 00:18:03,138
Here l am.

259
00:18:03,382 --> 00:18:04,940
Karl.

260
00:18:05,117 --> 00:18:07,984
Your mother is calling you.

261
00:18:08,687 --> 00:18:10,814
Your mother is...

262
00:18:10,989 --> 00:18:12,616
...with us.

263
00:18:14,660 --> 00:18:15,752
Talk to me.

264
00:18:20,065 --> 00:18:22,431
-l see you.
-Karl.

265
00:18:23,368 --> 00:18:25,529
Karl, my son.

266
00:18:26,371 --> 00:18:29,101
-l hear you.
-Karl.

267
00:18:29,541 --> 00:18:32,032
Don't be unhappy.

268
00:18:32,211 --> 00:18:35,146
lt's very beautiful here.

269
00:18:35,514 --> 00:18:37,709
l am at peace.

270
00:18:38,117 --> 00:18:43,384
There is no pain, no sickness,
no sorrow.

271
00:18:44,022 --> 00:18:47,287
l am watching over you, Karl.

272
00:18:48,360 --> 00:18:51,056
We will meet again...

273
00:18:51,864 --> 00:18:54,332
...soon.

274
00:18:54,500 --> 00:18:56,900
-Come back!
-No.

275
00:18:57,269 --> 00:18:59,237
No, l can't.

276
00:18:59,404 --> 00:19:03,340
They've gone. l can't find them.

277
00:19:07,746 --> 00:19:09,407
Turn on the lights.

278
00:19:11,250 --> 00:19:14,151
-Mrs. Walters, are you all right?
-l'll get some water.

279
00:19:14,319 --> 00:19:16,947
l'm afraid l can go no further tonight.

280
00:19:17,756 --> 00:19:20,748
You will forgive me, now, won't you?
l'm so tired.

281
00:19:20,926 --> 00:19:23,827
-lt was wonderful, Mrs. Walters.
-An inspiration.

282
00:19:23,996 --> 00:19:25,623
We'll see you next Tuesday.

283
00:19:26,098 --> 00:19:28,623
Your hats and coats are in the hallway.

284
00:19:33,605 --> 00:19:34,840
-You coming, doc?
-l'm going to talk to Mrs. Walters.

285
00:19:34,840 --> 00:19:37,240
-You coming, doc?
-l'm going to talk to Mrs. Walters.

286
00:19:38,544 --> 00:19:41,604
l congratulate you.
l've seen a lot of mediums at work...

287
00:19:41,780 --> 00:19:45,477
...but l think yours is one of the
smoothest performances l've ever seen.

288
00:19:46,518 --> 00:19:49,749
You're not the first unbeliever l've met.

289
00:19:49,922 --> 00:19:54,450
But other men of science have turned
to the occult for surcease from sorrow.

290
00:19:54,626 --> 00:19:56,890
Sir Oliver Lodge was a believer.

291
00:19:57,129 --> 00:20:00,462
-So was Sir Arthur Conan Doyle.
-l know, Mrs. Walters.

292
00:20:00,632 --> 00:20:05,763
But l am quite sure that l can duplicate
every trick you've done here tonight.

293
00:20:12,978 --> 00:20:16,106
l hate to disillusion you, Karl...

294
00:20:16,381 --> 00:20:18,849
...but there's your mother's ghost.

295
00:20:19,451 --> 00:20:21,681
And the voice...

296
00:20:23,255 --> 00:20:25,416
...came from...

297
00:20:27,659 --> 00:20:28,853
...here.

298
00:20:29,027 --> 00:20:30,426
There's just one thing more--

299
00:20:30,596 --> 00:20:32,154
Get out of here, both of you.

300
00:20:32,331 --> 00:20:33,923
Get out.

301
00:20:34,866 --> 00:20:38,029
After you've explained
one trick that's new to me.

302
00:20:38,203 --> 00:20:40,865
How do you handle
the wiring for that table?

303
00:20:41,206 --> 00:20:42,195
What wiring?

304
00:20:42,374 --> 00:20:46,936
l experienced a severe shock during
the séance, a dangerously high voltage.

305
00:20:47,112 --> 00:20:50,275
lt might prove fatal to some
of your more elderly clients.

306
00:20:51,783 --> 00:20:56,152
Are you crazy? l've never used
electricity in a séance in my life.

307
00:20:56,989 --> 00:20:59,219
ls that the truth?

308
00:20:59,758 --> 00:21:01,191
Why should l lie to you now?

309
00:21:04,730 --> 00:21:07,130
What if that's true?

310
00:21:07,566 --> 00:21:09,591
lf that impulse...

311
00:21:09,768 --> 00:21:12,293
...is really generated by your own brain...

312
00:21:12,471 --> 00:21:15,463
...and your nervous system
without your knowledge, then....

313
00:21:15,641 --> 00:21:18,132
lf that's possible.

314
00:21:18,944 --> 00:21:21,913
Mrs. Walters, l'd like you to come
to my laboratory now.

315
00:21:22,080 --> 00:21:23,547
l'd like to make a test.

316
00:21:23,715 --> 00:21:25,842
-Why?
-lt may be that you're closer...

317
00:21:26,018 --> 00:21:29,545
...to a real communication
with the dead than you ever realized.

318
00:21:30,922 --> 00:21:34,153
l'm not in this business
for my health, Dr. Blair.

319
00:21:35,193 --> 00:21:39,152
lf you can help me in my work,
you'll be well-paid.

320
00:21:41,566 --> 00:21:43,796
l'll get my coat.

321
00:21:48,740 --> 00:21:49,741
<i>I waited for my father at home</i>
<i>that night.</i>

322
00:21:49,741 --> 00:21:52,107
<i>I waited for my father at home</i>
<i>that night.</i>

323
00:21:52,277 --> 00:21:54,507
<i>I didn't know what to do.</i>

324
00:21:54,680 --> 00:21:57,046
<i>I didn't know where he was.</i>

325
00:21:57,215 --> 00:22:00,844
<i>And all the time, he was locked</i>
<i>up there in his laboratory...</i>

326
00:22:01,019 --> 00:22:04,420
<i>...with Karl and Mrs. Walters.</i>

327
00:22:04,990 --> 00:22:08,187
<i>All he could think of was</i>
<i>how to reach my mother...</i>

328
00:22:08,360 --> 00:22:10,419
<i>...how to talk to her.</i>

329
00:22:10,595 --> 00:22:13,621
<i>He thought Mrs. Walters</i>
<i>might be able to help him.</i>

330
00:22:13,799 --> 00:22:17,633
<i>He wasn't sure,</i>
<i>but he had to find out.</i>

331
00:22:18,236 --> 00:22:19,863
<i>And that...</i>

332
00:22:20,172 --> 00:22:22,697
<i>...that was the beginning.</i>

333
00:22:24,810 --> 00:22:27,540
l think you'd better
take off that ring.

334
00:22:33,151 --> 00:22:35,551
Stand back, Karl.

335
00:22:39,424 --> 00:22:41,392
Are you afraid?

336
00:22:52,471 --> 00:22:54,439
Now watch those lights.

337
00:23:04,883 --> 00:23:08,182
Your brain and nervous system
are producing an electrical current.

338
00:23:08,353 --> 00:23:11,049
An incredibly high voltage.

339
00:23:18,597 --> 00:23:22,363
Dr. Blair, l think it's time you
told me what this is all about.

340
00:23:22,534 --> 00:23:27,028
This is science, Mrs. Walters.
There's nothing of the occult about it.

341
00:23:27,939 --> 00:23:31,204
lf you can produce an electrical
voltage as powerful as that...

342
00:23:31,376 --> 00:23:35,073
...the next step is to see if
you can absorb as much or more.

343
00:23:35,247 --> 00:23:36,407
And if l can?

344
00:23:36,581 --> 00:23:39,141
Then you may serve
the same purpose...

345
00:23:39,317 --> 00:23:42,684
...as the ground and aerials serve
in radio sending and receiving.

346
00:23:42,854 --> 00:23:45,448
But l can't be sure
until l make a further test.

347
00:23:45,624 --> 00:23:49,424
Karl, you can help me, if you will.
You can take that off now.

348
00:23:51,196 --> 00:23:53,721
Let's move this out here, Karl.

349
00:23:54,299 --> 00:23:58,395
Far enough. Over here,
if you please, Mrs. Walters.

350
00:24:09,014 --> 00:24:11,107
Stand back, Karl.

351
00:24:17,189 --> 00:24:18,816
All ready?

352
00:24:45,884 --> 00:24:47,374
Karl!

353
00:24:53,458 --> 00:24:55,085
l'm all right.

354
00:24:55,594 --> 00:24:59,621
Do you realize that 2000 volts would
electrocute the ordinary human being...

355
00:24:59,798 --> 00:25:03,564
...but 1 0,000 passed through your body
a moment ago without harming you?

356
00:25:04,336 --> 00:25:08,898
l believe l'm on the right track.
Let me show you something.

357
00:25:16,047 --> 00:25:21,144
That wave, that impulse was recorded
by my wife's brain before she died.

358
00:25:21,319 --> 00:25:24,311
That was recorded after
she was dead and buried.

359
00:25:24,489 --> 00:25:27,890
That proves that that brain impulse
still lives somewhere.

360
00:25:28,326 --> 00:25:30,385
What has that got to do with me?

361
00:25:30,562 --> 00:25:35,556
l believe that if l could change
the hookup on that recording machine...

362
00:25:35,734 --> 00:25:38,464
...so that instead of recording
your brain waves...

363
00:25:38,637 --> 00:25:41,800
...l could utilize the energy output
and receiving field...

364
00:25:41,973 --> 00:25:46,137
...of an abnormally sensitized
human being, like you, for instance.

365
00:25:46,511 --> 00:25:50,709
l could bring in that impulse so strongly
that l could record it constantly...

366
00:25:51,182 --> 00:25:54,049
...and perhaps learn
to read its message.

367
00:25:54,486 --> 00:25:59,423
Eventually, l may bring back
my wife's actual voice...

368
00:25:59,591 --> 00:26:02,389
...and show the world
how to talk to those who have...

369
00:26:02,561 --> 00:26:04,552
...passed beyond the grave.

370
00:26:04,729 --> 00:26:09,325
lf you can do what you're trying
to do, you'll own the world.

371
00:26:09,501 --> 00:26:10,991
You know that, don't you?

372
00:26:11,970 --> 00:26:14,837
You sit down and rest for a while.

373
00:26:15,006 --> 00:26:16,701
Then we'll see.

374
00:26:34,092 --> 00:26:36,083
<i>My father didn't come home.</i>

375
00:26:36,261 --> 00:26:38,354
<i>I didn't know what to do.</i>

376
00:26:38,530 --> 00:26:42,796
<i>Finally, I couldn't stand waiting,</i>
<i>wondering.</i>

377
00:26:42,968 --> 00:26:44,959
<i>I had to find him.</i>

378
00:26:45,704 --> 00:26:47,899
<i>I called Richard Sayles.</i>

379
00:27:12,964 --> 00:27:15,228
-Karl, do you want to help?
-Sure, doc.

380
00:27:15,400 --> 00:27:18,767
Then get a chair and put
it next to Mrs. Walters. Hurry.

381
00:27:23,441 --> 00:27:25,807
l'm going to add Karl to the circuit.

382
00:27:25,977 --> 00:27:28,912
lt may add to the receiving strength
of the machines...

383
00:27:29,080 --> 00:27:32,049
...just like adding radio tubes to a set.

384
00:27:35,487 --> 00:27:37,114
ln a little bit, Karl.

385
00:27:37,288 --> 00:27:39,188
That's right.

386
00:27:39,357 --> 00:27:40,915
Now sit down.

387
00:27:50,535 --> 00:27:53,470
lt's all right, Karl.
lt's not going to hurt you.

388
00:28:47,992 --> 00:28:49,459
Helen.

389
00:28:58,336 --> 00:28:59,633
Helen!

390
00:29:00,105 --> 00:29:02,335
Helen.

391
00:29:02,607 --> 00:29:03,972
Helen.

392
00:29:08,913 --> 00:29:10,505
Karl.

393
00:29:13,251 --> 00:29:15,014
Help me.

394
00:29:26,331 --> 00:29:28,663
-Who is that?
-l don't know.

395
00:29:28,833 --> 00:29:31,324
We'd better not let anybody
see him the way he is now.

396
00:29:31,503 --> 00:29:32,868
No.

397
00:29:35,240 --> 00:29:38,676
l'll take care of him.
Go see who it is.

398
00:29:50,755 --> 00:29:52,313
Dad, we've come to get you.

399
00:29:52,490 --> 00:29:54,082
Do you know what time it is?

400
00:29:54,325 --> 00:29:55,792
Of course.

401
00:29:59,130 --> 00:30:01,655
Dad, come home.

402
00:30:01,833 --> 00:30:03,824
l thought l asked you
not to bother me.

403
00:30:04,002 --> 00:30:07,335
Doctor, l don't like
to say this to you, but...

404
00:30:07,505 --> 00:30:09,735
...well, people are talking about you.

405
00:30:09,908 --> 00:30:13,071
And there's to be a report
given at the university board...

406
00:30:13,244 --> 00:30:14,233
...that...

407
00:30:14,512 --> 00:30:17,481
-...well, that you....
-That l'm losing my mind.

408
00:30:17,916 --> 00:30:19,440
Thank you for telling me.

409
00:30:19,617 --> 00:30:21,414
Now will you leave me alone?

410
00:30:21,586 --> 00:30:23,781
-Dad, please.
-Good night.

411
00:30:33,665 --> 00:30:35,098
Look at Karl.

412
00:30:35,266 --> 00:30:36,631
Karl. Karl.

413
00:30:37,335 --> 00:30:41,567
l'm afraid electric shock has injured
his nerve centers, perhaps permanently.

414
00:30:42,674 --> 00:30:45,609
The impulse had begun
to come through. lt was Helen...

415
00:30:46,244 --> 00:30:48,007
...and now Karl, like this.

416
00:30:48,179 --> 00:30:52,878
The world can get along without him,
and nobody has to know about this.

417
00:30:53,051 --> 00:30:55,212
We can't hide him.
He has to have care.

418
00:30:55,386 --> 00:30:59,516
lf anyone sees him the way he is,
the law will step in and stop you for good.

419
00:30:59,924 --> 00:31:00,982
l know.

420
00:31:01,159 --> 00:31:04,128
Have you got enough money
to leave this town and take Karl?

421
00:31:04,295 --> 00:31:06,525
-What?
-We've got to get away from here.

422
00:31:06,698 --> 00:31:09,565
Where you can go on working
and no one will know.

423
00:31:12,103 --> 00:31:13,593
Yes.

424
00:31:15,840 --> 00:31:17,239
Yes.

425
00:31:20,612 --> 00:31:25,049
<i>The next morning,</i>
<i>my father sent me away to New York.</i>

426
00:31:25,216 --> 00:31:27,810
<i>He resigned at the university.</i>

427
00:31:27,986 --> 00:31:30,853
<i>He arranged to sell our house.</i>

428
00:31:31,723 --> 00:31:35,523
<i>He said he was going away</i>
<i>that same day.</i>

429
00:31:35,693 --> 00:31:38,127
<i>He wouldn't tell me where.</i>

430
00:31:38,296 --> 00:31:42,699
<i>He said he'd write to me later</i>
<i>if he could.</i>

431
00:31:43,768 --> 00:31:45,998
<i>He was like a stranger.</i>

432
00:31:46,170 --> 00:31:49,037
<i>Someone I'd</i>--
<i>I'd never known.</i>

433
00:31:49,207 --> 00:31:53,337
<i>And yet, he hadn't stopped loving me.</i>
<i>I know he hadn't.</i>

434
00:31:55,280 --> 00:31:56,542
Goodbye, Anne.

435
00:31:58,783 --> 00:32:00,182
Goodbye.

436
00:32:12,897 --> 00:32:17,197
<i>I didn't see my father again</i>
<i>for two years.</i>

437
00:32:17,368 --> 00:32:20,895
<i>Every three months,</i>
<i>he sent me a check.</i>

438
00:32:21,072 --> 00:32:23,666
<i>He never wrote me a letter.</i>

439
00:32:23,841 --> 00:32:27,368
<i>I wrote to him,</i>
<i>but he never answered.</i>

440
00:32:28,246 --> 00:32:33,513
<i>He bought a strange house at Barsham</i>
<i>Harbor on the New England coast.</i>

441
00:32:33,685 --> 00:32:35,983
<i>There, he went on with his work.</i>

442
00:32:36,154 --> 00:32:39,920
<i>On and on and on.</i>

443
00:32:41,793 --> 00:32:46,127
<i>People in Barsham Harbor</i>
<i>didn't understand my father.</i>

444
00:32:46,297 --> 00:32:48,492
<i>They began to talk about him.</i>

445
00:32:49,033 --> 00:32:53,367
<i>Slowly, they began to fear him</i>
<i>and then to hate him...</i>

446
00:32:53,538 --> 00:32:56,336
<i>...without really knowing why.</i>

447
00:32:56,674 --> 00:33:00,132
<i>Poison of hate</i>
<i>spread through the village.</i>

448
00:33:00,311 --> 00:33:02,336
<i>No one would even speak to him...</i>

449
00:33:02,513 --> 00:33:05,243
<i>...although he had never</i>
<i>hurt any of them.</i>

450
00:33:05,416 --> 00:33:07,043
<i>You must remember that.</i>

451
00:33:07,218 --> 00:33:11,245
<i>My father never hurt a living person</i>
<i>in Barsham Harbor.</i>

452
00:33:11,422 --> 00:33:12,855
<i>Never.</i>

453
00:33:45,123 --> 00:33:47,785
-Why, Sheriff Ed.
-Evening, Mrs. Marcy.

454
00:33:47,959 --> 00:33:52,293
What on earth you doing way out here?
Come on inside.

455
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:59,026
l asked you what you're doing
way out here.

456
00:33:59,203 --> 00:34:02,434
-Oh, business, Mrs. Marcy.
-Sheriff business?

457
00:34:03,508 --> 00:34:05,408
ln a way.

458
00:34:05,576 --> 00:34:07,271
Your husband around anywhere?

459
00:34:07,445 --> 00:34:09,538
Seth Marcy ain't set foot
on these premises...

460
00:34:09,714 --> 00:34:12,979
...the two years l been working here,
and swears he never will.

461
00:34:13,151 --> 00:34:15,244
Seth don't like Dr. Blair.

462
00:34:15,420 --> 00:34:18,082
From what l hear,
he's not the only one that don't.

463
00:34:18,790 --> 00:34:22,089
-You better call Dr. Blair.
-l wouldn't dare go near him.

464
00:34:22,260 --> 00:34:24,990
-Why not?
-He's working in his laboratory.

465
00:34:25,163 --> 00:34:27,597
l got strict orders
never to go near that place.

466
00:34:27,765 --> 00:34:28,754
This is important.

467
00:34:28,933 --> 00:34:31,663
Wouldn't matter if the world
was ending tomorrow.

468
00:34:31,836 --> 00:34:33,997
She wouldn't let you bother him.

469
00:34:34,172 --> 00:34:36,800
-She?
-Mrs. Walters.

470
00:34:36,974 --> 00:34:38,566
You seen her?

471
00:34:38,743 --> 00:34:40,404
l've heard of her.

472
00:34:41,479 --> 00:34:45,040
Have you noticed anything
peculiar going on around here?

473
00:34:45,249 --> 00:34:48,377
l make it my business not to notice
what ain't my business.

474
00:34:48,553 --> 00:34:51,716
How do you get along with that ape
that follows the doc around?

475
00:34:51,889 --> 00:34:54,187
Karl?
He's harmless.

476
00:34:54,358 --> 00:34:56,087
He's like a big, ugly dog.

477
00:34:56,260 --> 00:35:00,219
All you have to do is raise
your voice to him, and he minds.

478
00:35:03,768 --> 00:35:05,065
Hey...

479
00:35:06,637 --> 00:35:08,764
...why haven't you got electric lights?

480
00:35:09,107 --> 00:35:12,565
Mrs. Walters says they'd interfere
with the reception.

481
00:35:12,743 --> 00:35:15,109
-Reception of what?
-l don't know.

482
00:35:15,279 --> 00:35:18,407
He's inventing some kind of radio,
l guess.

483
00:35:22,887 --> 00:35:25,151
You. Stand still.

484
00:35:25,323 --> 00:35:28,087
Ed Willis, you put that gun away.
Karl, you stop.

485
00:35:32,563 --> 00:35:34,360
Karl, you hear me?

486
00:35:40,171 --> 00:35:44,073
Just like l told you.
Karl minds when he's spoken to.

487
00:35:49,914 --> 00:35:51,711
What was that noise?

488
00:35:52,216 --> 00:35:55,049
Some kind of static, l suppose,
from the laboratory.

489
00:35:55,219 --> 00:35:57,585
l got used to it long ago.

490
00:36:11,302 --> 00:36:14,669
-What do you want?
-l'd like to talk to Dr. Blair.

491
00:36:15,706 --> 00:36:17,037
That's impossible.

492
00:36:17,408 --> 00:36:19,342
l don't think so.

493
00:36:20,411 --> 00:36:25,314
Doc, do you want to come down here,
or shall l come up?

494
00:36:27,885 --> 00:36:31,821
Maybe l should explain
that l'm sheriff of this county.

495
00:36:32,623 --> 00:36:35,615
The name's Willis.
Ed Willis.

496
00:36:35,793 --> 00:36:38,956
-l don't care who you are.
-How about it, doc?

497
00:36:48,139 --> 00:36:50,232
You don't have to talk to him.

498
00:36:50,408 --> 00:36:53,377
Might make things a lot better
all around if he did.

499
00:36:53,544 --> 00:36:55,034
Why?

500
00:36:56,047 --> 00:36:58,072
An old settler named Sam Jennings...

501
00:36:58,249 --> 00:37:01,707
...was buried in the family vault
day before yesterday.

502
00:37:01,886 --> 00:37:02,875
Well?

503
00:37:03,554 --> 00:37:05,818
His body disappeared last night.

504
00:37:06,157 --> 00:37:08,216
Why tell us about that?

505
00:37:08,392 --> 00:37:10,360
Mostly because it's happened before.

506
00:37:12,029 --> 00:37:14,190
Four times before.

507
00:37:15,132 --> 00:37:19,091
Five bodies missing in the two years
since you people came to this town.

508
00:37:19,937 --> 00:37:22,667
And it never happened
before you came to town.

509
00:37:23,541 --> 00:37:26,772
Now, it's my job to find out
who stole those bodies.

510
00:37:30,281 --> 00:37:32,010
We don't know anything about it.

511
00:37:32,383 --> 00:37:35,113
Ordinarily, l don't pay attention
to what people say.

512
00:37:35,286 --> 00:37:37,811
l figure they've gotta
talk about something.

513
00:37:37,989 --> 00:37:40,423
But when a whole town
begins to talk about...

514
00:37:40,591 --> 00:37:43,651
...a connection between
the missing bodies...

515
00:37:43,828 --> 00:37:46,490
...and whatever it is
that goes on in this house...

516
00:37:46,664 --> 00:37:50,293
...well, l figure it's time
l found out what is going on.

517
00:37:51,769 --> 00:37:55,398
This is not the first time l've been
the victim of people who talk...

518
00:37:55,573 --> 00:37:58,804
...about things they're
too ignorant to understand.

519
00:38:01,512 --> 00:38:04,310
l'm engaged in experimental work.

520
00:38:04,482 --> 00:38:07,451
All right.
What kind of experiments?

521
00:38:07,618 --> 00:38:09,142
That's none of your business.

522
00:38:09,320 --> 00:38:12,619
l think it is, under the circumstances.

523
00:38:13,324 --> 00:38:14,916
Dr. Blair...

524
00:38:15,760 --> 00:38:17,853
...l want you to take me
to your laboratory.

525
00:38:18,029 --> 00:38:20,088
Show me just what it is
you are doing...

526
00:38:20,298 --> 00:38:22,061
...tell me what it's all about.

527
00:38:22,233 --> 00:38:24,565
Then l can go back to town
and tell the folks.

528
00:38:24,735 --> 00:38:26,464
Tell them you're okay.

529
00:38:26,637 --> 00:38:31,199
And l'll make them quit talking
before the talk goes too far.

530
00:38:31,609 --> 00:38:34,635
Now, that's fair enough, isn't it?

531
00:38:34,812 --> 00:38:39,511
lt'd be impossible to explain to you
what l'm doing, even if l wanted to.

532
00:38:39,684 --> 00:38:44,917
l believe l have the right to go on with my
work without being put on trial by fools.

533
00:38:45,456 --> 00:38:48,425
This is my house.
l've committed no crime. Karl.

534
00:38:52,763 --> 00:38:57,996
You will take this gentleman to the gate
and see that he leaves. That's all.

535
00:39:06,777 --> 00:39:08,108
Good night.

536
00:39:26,997 --> 00:39:28,794
That's all for tonight.

537
00:39:30,101 --> 00:39:34,037
-Good night, Dr. Blair.
-Good night, Mrs. Marcy.

538
00:39:35,339 --> 00:39:37,864
That man will be back.

539
00:39:38,042 --> 00:39:40,943
l'll take care of him when he comes.

540
00:39:42,012 --> 00:39:43,639
You'd better get some rest.

541
00:39:43,814 --> 00:39:48,046
No, l think l'm going to work
a little later tonight.

542
00:39:49,787 --> 00:39:51,220
Good night.

543
00:40:59,323 --> 00:41:02,087
Oh, it's you, Sheriff Ed.

544
00:41:02,259 --> 00:41:04,989
-You scared me out of me year's growth.
-Sorry.

545
00:41:05,162 --> 00:41:08,723
l didn't turn on the headlights, in case
anybody was watching. Come on.

546
00:41:08,899 --> 00:41:10,890
Come on, get in.
l'll drive you home.

547
00:41:24,315 --> 00:41:27,045
You certainly caused
plenty of excitement tonight.

548
00:41:27,218 --> 00:41:30,244
How on earth could you
practically accuse poor Dr. Blair...

549
00:41:30,421 --> 00:41:33,447
...of stealing bodies?

550
00:41:34,158 --> 00:41:36,820
Well, somebody stole them.

551
00:41:37,761 --> 00:41:39,592
What's in that laboratory of his?

552
00:41:39,763 --> 00:41:43,028
l never been in it.
The door's always kept locked.

553
00:41:43,200 --> 00:41:47,227
-Could you get in?
-And get caught and lose my job?

554
00:41:47,404 --> 00:41:50,339
l never was inquisitive,
and l see no reason to be now...

555
00:41:50,508 --> 00:41:52,373
...just to satisfy your curiosity.

556
00:41:54,512 --> 00:41:58,710
Look, Mrs. Marcy. l'm not saying there's
anything really wrong in that house.

557
00:41:58,883 --> 00:42:03,752
But a lot of folks are thinking there is
unless l can tell them differently.

558
00:42:04,522 --> 00:42:08,549
You know, folks can talk just so long,
and then there's an explosion.

559
00:42:08,726 --> 00:42:11,752
And a lot of people get hurt.

560
00:42:11,929 --> 00:42:15,296
l don't want any mob trouble
in our town.

561
00:42:15,466 --> 00:42:18,560
Maybe you could help
to keep that from happening.

562
00:42:19,937 --> 00:42:20,961
Will you try?

563
00:42:23,007 --> 00:42:26,033
l never made a promise yet
and didn't keep it.

564
00:42:26,210 --> 00:42:29,179
So l ain't gonna promise you a thing...

565
00:42:29,346 --> 00:42:31,007
...but l'll see.

566
00:44:28,666 --> 00:44:30,190
Karl...

567
00:44:30,834 --> 00:44:34,531
...l forgot to lock the laboratory.
Take care of it for me, will you?

568
00:45:42,873 --> 00:45:47,105
Let me out! Let me out!
Let me out!

569
00:46:09,500 --> 00:46:11,730
Dr. Blair. Dr. Blair!

570
00:46:14,438 --> 00:46:18,306
Dr. Blair! Dr. Blair! Dr. Blair!

571
00:46:26,416 --> 00:46:28,247
Who's in there?

572
00:46:28,418 --> 00:46:29,646
Where are the keys?

573
00:46:39,997 --> 00:46:41,521
Stand back.

574
00:47:03,120 --> 00:47:04,985
ls she dead?

575
00:47:07,958 --> 00:47:08,947
Yes.

576
00:47:09,126 --> 00:47:13,324
-How'd she get in here?
-l forgot to lock the door.

577
00:47:13,497 --> 00:47:16,091
Now l am a criminal,
a murderer.

578
00:47:16,266 --> 00:47:20,202
When she doesn't come home tonight,
her husband will start looking for her.

579
00:47:20,370 --> 00:47:24,067
-Then how? What?
-There's only one thing we can do.

580
00:48:07,117 --> 00:48:08,584
They're here.

581
00:48:08,752 --> 00:48:12,415
-Who?
-Seth Marcy and the sheriff.

582
00:48:12,589 --> 00:48:16,423
You'll have to talk to them.
They won't leave unless you do.

583
00:48:21,098 --> 00:48:23,896
l've taken care of the footprints.

584
00:48:26,236 --> 00:48:30,764
You'd better not keep the sheriff waiting
too long, or he might come up here.

585
00:48:37,214 --> 00:48:40,047
-Where's my wife?
-Easy, Seth.

586
00:48:40,217 --> 00:48:43,414
-l can't tell you anything about her.
-She left here hours ago.

587
00:48:43,687 --> 00:48:46,281
You're lying.
She's here in this house somewhere.

588
00:48:46,723 --> 00:48:48,520
l'd like to help you,
but l can't.

589
00:48:48,692 --> 00:48:50,284
How do l know she's not here?

590
00:48:50,460 --> 00:48:53,657
What would she be doing here
at this time of night?

591
00:48:54,665 --> 00:48:57,930
You have time to help them look for her,
haven't you, Dr. Blair?

592
00:48:58,101 --> 00:49:01,468
Yes, l'll get my hat and coat.

593
00:49:02,306 --> 00:49:04,001
Look where?

594
00:49:04,808 --> 00:49:07,106
She always went home
the same way, didn't she?

595
00:49:08,078 --> 00:49:11,980
The path leads right along
the edge of the cliff at one place.

596
00:49:12,749 --> 00:49:13,943
l know it does.

597
00:49:15,218 --> 00:49:16,845
Come on, Seth.

598
00:50:14,745 --> 00:50:18,374
lt was dark when Mrs. Marcy
left the house.

599
00:50:18,548 --> 00:50:22,814
We asked her if she wanted a lantern,
but she said she didn't need one.

600
00:50:22,986 --> 00:50:28,014
She walked that path day or night,
rain or shine, for two years.

601
00:50:28,191 --> 00:50:30,921
She wouldn't have walked over here.

602
00:50:31,628 --> 00:50:32,822
What did you do to her?

603
00:50:32,996 --> 00:50:35,658
l didn't do anything to her.
l'm....

604
00:50:35,832 --> 00:50:38,460
-l'm terribly sorry.
-Seth.

605
00:50:40,937 --> 00:50:43,735
May l go home, please?

606
00:50:43,907 --> 00:50:46,034
Yes, you might as well.

607
00:50:48,612 --> 00:50:52,309
l'd be glad to help to pay
for the funeral expenses...

608
00:50:52,482 --> 00:50:55,212
...in case you find--

609
00:50:55,385 --> 00:50:56,977
Good night.

610
00:51:06,563 --> 00:51:08,656
They've killed her.

611
00:51:08,832 --> 00:51:10,322
Seth!

612
00:51:11,768 --> 00:51:13,793
Now, l know how you feel...

613
00:51:13,970 --> 00:51:16,268
...but l can't stand for you
starting any trouble.

614
00:51:16,440 --> 00:51:19,068
You've got absolutely nothing to go on...

615
00:51:19,242 --> 00:51:21,608
...nothing but loose talk
and superstition...

616
00:51:21,778 --> 00:51:24,906
...and the fact that you
never did like Dr. Blair.

617
00:51:25,916 --> 00:51:28,749
Now, you go around
talking too much and....

618
00:51:28,919 --> 00:51:31,911
Well, l might just have
to put a stop to it.

619
00:51:33,457 --> 00:51:35,550
Go on home now, Seth.

620
00:51:45,068 --> 00:51:47,628
Well, are they satisfied?

621
00:51:47,804 --> 00:51:49,795
Why did you follow us?

622
00:51:50,540 --> 00:51:53,998
We could honestly have said
her death was accidental.

623
00:51:54,177 --> 00:51:56,111
Now we've lied.

624
00:51:56,279 --> 00:52:00,773
-We're as guilty as if we'd planned this.
-Stop talking like that.

625
00:52:00,951 --> 00:52:03,681
Come on.
We can't stay here now.

626
00:52:07,958 --> 00:52:12,418
<i>Richard and I reached Barsham Harbor</i>
<i>very late that night.</i>

627
00:52:12,596 --> 00:52:16,191
<i>The sheriff told us what he thought</i>
<i>had happened to Mrs. Marcy...</i>

628
00:52:16,366 --> 00:52:19,233
<i>...and hinted much more than he said.</i>

629
00:52:20,170 --> 00:52:25,437
<i>He told us Seth Marcy was telling</i>
<i>everyone my father had killed his wife.</i>

630
00:52:26,309 --> 00:52:30,143
<i>The sheriff told us so much</i>
<i>we could hardly believe him.</i>

631
00:52:31,047 --> 00:52:34,574
<i>My father had become</i>
<i>a very strange man.</i>

632
00:52:35,385 --> 00:52:37,512
<i>While we were on our way</i>
<i>to his house...</i>

633
00:52:37,687 --> 00:52:41,453
<i>...he was working</i>
<i>in that ghastly place.</i>

634
00:52:54,704 --> 00:52:57,696
Karl, go over to the other wall
and fix your safety belt.

635
00:53:43,553 --> 00:53:45,077
Stand back, please.

636
00:53:51,194 --> 00:53:53,822
The sooner you take charge
in there, the better.

637
00:54:14,517 --> 00:54:15,575
Helen.

638
00:54:23,293 --> 00:54:25,056
Look out, let me.

639
00:54:31,434 --> 00:54:33,595
-You better stay down here, Anne.
-No.

640
00:54:43,280 --> 00:54:47,182
Let me out. No.
l can't stand it.

641
00:54:47,484 --> 00:54:49,076
<i>Julian.</i>

642
00:54:55,225 --> 00:54:56,249
Helen.

643
00:54:59,329 --> 00:55:01,627
Stop. l can't stand it.

644
00:55:04,034 --> 00:55:05,501
<i>Julian.</i>

645
00:55:06,169 --> 00:55:07,500
Helen.

646
00:55:07,671 --> 00:55:09,161
No, let me out.

647
00:55:37,967 --> 00:55:39,400
Mrs. Walters.

648
00:55:43,373 --> 00:55:44,704
Mrs. Walters.

649
00:55:46,676 --> 00:55:50,168
Karl, don't open that door.

650
00:56:03,159 --> 00:56:04,820
Anne.

651
00:56:05,228 --> 00:56:07,162
Oh, Dad.

652
00:56:07,697 --> 00:56:08,925
l sent for her.

653
00:56:09,499 --> 00:56:13,265
Told her she'd better come here
and take care of you.

654
00:56:14,003 --> 00:56:16,369
Dad, why didn't you
answer my letters?

655
00:56:16,539 --> 00:56:19,406
-Well, you never wrote me.
-But l did.

656
00:56:19,576 --> 00:56:22,545
l saw a letter at the post office myself.

657
00:56:23,012 --> 00:56:25,742
That's how l knew
where to get in touch with her.

658
00:56:25,915 --> 00:56:28,543
But Mrs. Walters always--

659
00:56:31,654 --> 00:56:35,590
l should have realized long ago.

660
00:56:36,593 --> 00:56:39,960
You've done me a favor,
a great favor.

661
00:56:40,130 --> 00:56:43,361
There'll be no more trouble
in this house...

662
00:56:43,533 --> 00:56:46,730
-...now that my daughter is here.
-l'll be in touch later, sheriff.

663
00:56:46,903 --> 00:56:49,599
All right.
Good night.

664
00:56:52,108 --> 00:56:54,770
You'll find a lamp
downstairs in the kitchen.

665
00:56:54,944 --> 00:56:57,242
You'll be wanting something
to eat, won't you?

666
00:56:57,414 --> 00:56:59,006
l'll come talk to you later.

667
00:56:59,182 --> 00:57:02,242
-But, doctor, why--?
-l'll be down in a few minutes, Richard.

668
00:57:02,419 --> 00:57:06,788
l've got something to do.
lt won't take me very long.

669
00:57:07,891 --> 00:57:09,756
All right, Dad.

670
00:57:34,284 --> 00:57:36,650
You'll have to help me, Karl.

671
00:57:37,921 --> 00:57:40,549
Yes, she's dead.

672
00:57:44,561 --> 00:57:46,153
l thought you'd never get here.

673
00:57:46,329 --> 00:57:49,958
Seth's got them worked up to where
they're talking about lynching him.

674
00:57:50,266 --> 00:57:53,064
Not tonight, Seth.
Now go back home where you belong.

675
00:57:53,269 --> 00:57:57,399
-You ain't stopping us, Ed.
-l will. lf l have to use this.

676
00:57:57,574 --> 00:57:59,439
-Now, l'm warning you.
-Attaboy, Joe.

677
00:57:59,609 --> 00:58:01,668
Hold him. Come on, men.

678
00:58:04,113 --> 00:58:06,604
-You can't stop them now.
-Come on.

679
00:58:12,989 --> 00:58:16,686
No, Karl.
Come in, Richard.

680
00:58:18,862 --> 00:58:20,659
Come in, Richard.

681
00:58:33,443 --> 00:58:35,206
Doctor, are these...?

682
00:58:38,481 --> 00:58:41,644
Now you know why l couldn't
bring the sheriff in here.

683
00:58:41,818 --> 00:58:43,979
l never meant to kill anybody, Richard.

684
00:58:44,153 --> 00:58:48,146
And as soon as the work is finished,
l'm going to give myself up.

685
00:58:48,324 --> 00:58:52,624
Richard, we must go on
with the work. We are both scientists.

686
00:58:52,795 --> 00:58:54,126
You and Anne can help me.

687
00:58:54,297 --> 00:58:57,130
Do you think l'd let Anne
have anything to do with this?

688
00:58:58,134 --> 00:59:02,332
Helen spoke to me tonight.
l actually heard her voice.

689
00:59:03,206 --> 00:59:05,265
l found out something
l should've known...

690
00:59:05,441 --> 00:59:08,410
...something l should've realized
a long time ago.

691
00:59:08,578 --> 00:59:13,447
Every time Helen's tried to speak
to me since she died...

692
00:59:13,616 --> 00:59:15,550
...Anne has been somewhere near.

693
00:59:16,219 --> 00:59:20,315
-What are you trying to tell me?
-Anne is the key.

694
00:59:20,490 --> 00:59:22,321
Don't you understand, Richard?

695
00:59:22,492 --> 00:59:26,053
The impulse that belongs to Anne
is almost identical with her mother's.

696
00:59:26,229 --> 00:59:28,629
Their minds are in tune.

697
00:59:28,798 --> 00:59:30,390
Tonight...

698
00:59:30,567 --> 00:59:34,731
...for the first time,
l heard Helen's voice.

699
00:59:34,904 --> 00:59:38,499
And now with Anne to help me,
perhaps l can talk to her.

700
00:59:38,675 --> 00:59:41,041
Do you think l'd let you put Anne in that?

701
00:59:41,210 --> 00:59:44,111
Richard, she'll be perfectly safe.

702
00:59:44,647 --> 00:59:47,514
-l won't let you touch her.
-Oh, Richard.

703
00:59:47,684 --> 00:59:50,915
Don't try to stop me now.
Trust me. Help me.

704
00:59:51,154 --> 00:59:52,883
Richard.

705
00:59:53,890 --> 00:59:55,949
l'm going to take Anne
out of this place.

706
00:59:56,125 --> 00:59:58,389
Maybe l can keep her
from knowing about this.

707
00:59:58,561 --> 01:00:02,258
Richard, Anne cannot leave.

708
01:00:03,866 --> 01:00:06,460
Anne cannot leave.

709
01:00:17,146 --> 01:00:20,377
Karl! Don't touch him.

710
01:00:25,221 --> 01:00:27,689
He isn't badly hurt.

711
01:00:27,957 --> 01:00:31,586
You better take him to my room.
And that's all!

712
01:00:37,467 --> 01:00:41,335
Anne, dear,
l'm not going to hurt you.

713
01:00:41,537 --> 01:00:45,166
ln a few moments, we may hear
your mother's voice.

714
01:00:45,341 --> 01:00:49,607
We're very close to your mother now,
dear. l feel sure of it.

715
01:00:57,820 --> 01:01:02,382
l've got to use more amplification than
l've ever used before, but don't be afraid.

716
01:01:02,558 --> 01:01:06,324
You'll feel something pulling at you,
dragging you towards the table...

717
01:01:06,496 --> 01:01:08,327
...but l won't let that force hurt you.

718
01:01:08,498 --> 01:01:12,195
lf there's any danger,
you can trust me to turn it off.

719
01:01:51,941 --> 01:01:53,932
<i>Julian.</i>

720
01:01:55,778 --> 01:01:57,336
<i>Julian.</i>

721
01:01:57,513 --> 01:01:59,413
Helen!

722
01:02:00,750 --> 01:02:02,342
<i>Julian.</i>

723
01:02:03,119 --> 01:02:04,643
<i>Julian.</i>

724
01:02:05,621 --> 01:02:07,088
<i>Julian.</i>

725
01:02:07,256 --> 01:02:08,780
Helen.

726
01:02:09,926 --> 01:02:11,826
Helen!

727
01:02:27,477 --> 01:02:29,604
He's upstairs in his laboratory.

728
01:02:34,317 --> 01:02:37,150
Get out of the way, you.

729
01:02:38,554 --> 01:02:40,522
-Come on, boys!
-Get him!

730
01:02:55,004 --> 01:02:56,767
Helen.

731
01:03:14,357 --> 01:03:16,291
Anne!

732
01:03:19,362 --> 01:03:22,024
Anne. Anne!

733
01:03:24,333 --> 01:03:25,857
Anne, are you hurt?

734
01:03:26,035 --> 01:03:27,832
Anne!

735
01:03:32,708 --> 01:03:37,475
<i>They say my father's spirit</i>
<i>must still live in that house.</i>

736
01:03:37,980 --> 01:03:40,039
<i>I don't know.</i>

737
01:03:40,616 --> 01:03:43,608
<i>When he seemed to be so close</i>
<i>to what he sought...</i>

738
01:03:43,786 --> 01:03:46,414
<i>...something reached out for him.</i>

739
01:03:46,589 --> 01:03:51,458
<i>A warning that human beings</i>
<i>must not try to reach beyond death.</i>

740
01:03:52,829 --> 01:03:54,956
<i>I don't know.</i>

741
01:03:55,631 --> 01:03:58,099
<i>No one will ever know.</i>

742
01:03:59,135 --> 01:04:05,472
<i>And yet, perhaps the time will come</i>
<i>when the door to infinity will open.</i>

743
01:04:06,475 --> 01:04:08,807
<i>Perhaps.</i>

744
01:04:09,979 --> 01:04:12,072
<i>Perhaps.</i>
